WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.840
Good morning.

2
00:00:04.240 --> 00:00:06.900
Pray with me before we dive into the text today.

3
00:00:10.360 --> 00:00:13.520
Heavenly Father, we are so thankful

4
00:00:13.520 --> 00:00:16.240
that we get to come and worship you.

5
00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:21.840
Pray Lord that today you would reveal to us

6
00:00:22.740 --> 00:00:25.400
more about who you are, your goodness

7
00:00:25.400 --> 00:00:27.000
and your faithfulness to us.

8
00:00:27.360 --> 00:00:31.280
Pray all this in your name.

9
00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:32.120
Amen.

10
00:00:34.280 --> 00:00:35.400
All right.

11
00:00:35.400 --> 00:00:37.240
Well, to start off today,

12
00:00:37.240 --> 00:00:39.280
I'm just gonna go back to verse one

13
00:00:39.280 --> 00:00:41.520
and I just wanna read verse one again

14
00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:43.440
because there's a couple of things that stood out to me

15
00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:47.200
as I studied this passage this week from verse one.

16
00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:50.240
So Psalm 12 verse one says,

17
00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:54.720
save, oh Lord, for the godly one is gone,

18
00:00:54.760 --> 00:00:57.240
for the faithful have vanished

19
00:00:57.240 --> 00:00:58.980
from among the children of man.

20
00:01:00.440 --> 00:01:02.360
And I think that those words,

21
00:01:02.360 --> 00:01:04.840
those three words at the beginning

22
00:01:04.840 --> 00:01:08.780
really set the tone for what this passage is all about.

23
00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:15.120
David is crying out, save, oh Lord, or help me God.

24
00:01:16.480 --> 00:01:19.800
And that is the position,

25
00:01:19.800 --> 00:01:22.760
his position to God is one of needing help

26
00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:24.840
and recognizing that need for help.

27
00:01:24.840 --> 00:01:25.920
So I want us to keep that in mind

28
00:01:25.920 --> 00:01:27.280
as we move through the rest of this Psalm

29
00:01:27.280 --> 00:01:29.400
because that is kind of the core

30
00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:31.320
of what is being said here.

31
00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:34.220
David's need for help and reliance upon the Lord.

32
00:01:35.340 --> 00:01:37.420
I like how Charles Spurgeon put it

33
00:01:37.420 --> 00:01:42.420
when he was expositing on Psalm 12 verse one.

34
00:01:42.560 --> 00:01:46.600
He said, that help Lord is a short but sweet,

35
00:01:46.600 --> 00:01:50.600
suggestive, seasonable and serviceable prayer,

36
00:01:50.600 --> 00:01:53.400
kind of angel sword to be turned every way

37
00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:56.360
and to be used on all occasions.

38
00:01:56.360 --> 00:02:00.200
And isn't it true that that one phrase that help Lord

39
00:02:00.200 --> 00:02:04.080
is actually usable in any occasion?

40
00:02:04.080 --> 00:02:06.820
It's always applicable to our lives.

41
00:02:06.820 --> 00:02:08.360
We always need his help.

42
00:02:10.400 --> 00:02:13.160
One of my children, I won't say who it is,

43
00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:15.440
but whenever she changes clothes,

44
00:02:15.440 --> 00:02:19.120
she refuses help from anyone who tries to give it.

45
00:02:19.120 --> 00:02:21.520
The other day she kept trying to put her head

46
00:02:21.520 --> 00:02:23.780
into the armhole of one of her shirts.

47
00:02:25.120 --> 00:02:27.840
Obviously it didn't fit and she kept getting frustrated

48
00:02:27.840 --> 00:02:29.360
that it wasn't working.

49
00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:33.240
When I offered to help, obviously she refused.

50
00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:34.720
Her solution was that instead

51
00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:36.920
she needed to take her headband off her head

52
00:02:36.920 --> 00:02:38.680
and that maybe then that would work.

53
00:02:38.680 --> 00:02:39.880
And eventually it did work.

54
00:02:39.880 --> 00:02:42.600
Eventually she got her head to the right hole

55
00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:45.380
and she put her shirt on backwards.

56
00:02:46.140 --> 00:02:49.900
As kids, I think we can all look back on this and laugh

57
00:02:49.900 --> 00:02:51.940
and we might see kids or have kids in our own lives

58
00:02:51.940 --> 00:02:53.660
who act this similar way.

59
00:02:53.660 --> 00:02:56.860
Not wanting help, wanting to do it on our own.

60
00:02:56.860 --> 00:02:58.940
And that is often my tendency as well.

61
00:02:58.940 --> 00:03:01.820
And so I ask myself and I ask you this question

62
00:03:01.820 --> 00:03:04.340
kind of as leading into this text is,

63
00:03:04.340 --> 00:03:07.020
do you tend to avoid asking for help?

64
00:03:09.380 --> 00:03:12.980
Asking for help automatically puts us

65
00:03:12.980 --> 00:03:16.220
in a state of dependency on someone.

66
00:03:16.220 --> 00:03:18.820
Whoever it is we are asking for help from.

67
00:03:20.940 --> 00:03:25.940
David here recognizes he needs God's help.

68
00:03:26.620 --> 00:03:29.420
He comes right out of the gate and he starts with that.

69
00:03:29.420 --> 00:03:32.580
So that's the first thing that I noticed in this first one.

70
00:03:32.580 --> 00:03:35.660
The second thing is what is prompting David

71
00:03:35.660 --> 00:03:37.240
to cry for help?

72
00:03:38.500 --> 00:03:39.820
Well, if we look back at verse one,

73
00:03:39.820 --> 00:03:44.700
David's crying out for help because the godly one is gone

74
00:03:44.700 --> 00:03:46.920
and the faithful have vanished.

75
00:03:47.980 --> 00:03:48.980
Now what does this mean?

76
00:03:48.980 --> 00:03:50.980
Does this mean that there are no faithful,

77
00:03:50.980 --> 00:03:53.980
not a single faithful person left in the entire world?

78
00:03:53.980 --> 00:03:55.380
It's all gone.

79
00:03:56.500 --> 00:03:58.700
Well, I don't think that's quite what David is saying.

80
00:03:58.700 --> 00:04:00.460
The one could definitely make a case

81
00:04:00.460 --> 00:04:02.500
that even David had his shortcomings

82
00:04:02.500 --> 00:04:05.560
and had times where he was definitely not faithful to God.

83
00:04:06.860 --> 00:04:08.860
There's a couple of reasons why I would lean that way.

84
00:04:08.860 --> 00:04:11.580
One is there are two groups of people referenced here

85
00:04:11.580 --> 00:04:15.040
and one of them is referenced more explicitly than the other.

86
00:04:15.040 --> 00:04:20.040
The faithful who have vanished and the wicked

87
00:04:21.340 --> 00:04:24.140
who prowl on every side as we see in verse eight later.

88
00:04:25.240 --> 00:04:26.640
The second reason I think I'll lean this way

89
00:04:26.640 --> 00:04:30.420
is because David remembers God's promises to him

90
00:04:30.420 --> 00:04:33.600
and to Israel through him to establish his throne forever

91
00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:36.340
and appoint a place for Israel, his people.

92
00:04:37.340 --> 00:04:40.340
Later on in the story of Israel,

93
00:04:40.340 --> 00:04:42.860
we find that there are similar sentiments echoed

94
00:04:42.860 --> 00:04:45.380
by many prophets after David.

95
00:04:45.380 --> 00:04:49.740
One being Elijah in First Kings 1910 when he says,

96
00:04:50.900 --> 00:04:52.860
he's on the run from Jezebel right now.

97
00:04:52.860 --> 00:04:54.900
He's hiding in a cave and he says,

98
00:04:54.900 --> 00:04:59.300
I have been very jealous for the Lord, the God of hosts.

99
00:04:59.300 --> 00:05:02.340
For the people of Israel have forsaken your covenant,

100
00:05:02.340 --> 00:05:05.260
thrown down your altars, killed your prophets

101
00:05:05.300 --> 00:05:08.620
with the sword and I even I only am left

102
00:05:08.620 --> 00:05:11.220
and they seek my life to take it away.

103
00:05:11.220 --> 00:05:14.300
And he felt this same feeling that David is saying here,

104
00:05:14.300 --> 00:05:17.300
this I am alone, God, the faithful are gone.

105
00:05:17.300 --> 00:05:18.380
I don't know which way to turn.

106
00:05:18.380 --> 00:05:20.380
There's no one I can trust nearby.

107
00:05:23.020 --> 00:05:25.220
It's helpful for us to remember that for Elijah

108
00:05:25.220 --> 00:05:26.780
in verse 18 of that same chapter

109
00:05:26.780 --> 00:05:30.380
that God promises to leave a remnant of 7,000 in Israel.

110
00:05:30.380 --> 00:05:32.980
So we know that God's plan always contains

111
00:05:33.020 --> 00:05:35.740
this remnant of people who are his people

112
00:05:37.180 --> 00:05:39.140
who he will not leave and not forsake.

113
00:05:41.380 --> 00:05:44.860
We also hear this a similar type of message from Micah

114
00:05:44.860 --> 00:05:47.340
in Micah 7 verses 2 through 6.

115
00:05:47.340 --> 00:05:49.380
So I'm gonna turn there.

116
00:05:49.380 --> 00:05:51.060
If you have a Bible you wanna turn with me.

117
00:05:51.060 --> 00:05:53.180
I think this is a really good parallel passage

118
00:05:53.180 --> 00:05:54.700
to Psalm 12 as well.

119
00:05:54.700 --> 00:05:59.700
So I'm just gonna turn to Micah 7 verses 2 through 6

120
00:05:59.740 --> 00:06:03.100
and walk through some of what he says there as well.

121
00:06:05.540 --> 00:06:06.940
Micah 7 2 says,

122
00:06:06.940 --> 00:06:10.220
The godly has perished from the earth.

123
00:06:10.220 --> 00:06:12.900
There is no one upright among mankind.

124
00:06:12.900 --> 00:06:14.980
They all lie in wait for blood

125
00:06:14.980 --> 00:06:18.020
and each hunts the other with a net.

126
00:06:18.020 --> 00:06:21.420
Their hands are on what is evil to do it well.

127
00:06:21.420 --> 00:06:24.340
The prince and the judge ask for a bribe

128
00:06:24.340 --> 00:06:27.700
and the great man utters evil desire of his soul.

129
00:06:28.700 --> 00:06:30.660
Thus they weave it together.

130
00:06:30.660 --> 00:06:33.060
The best of them is like a briar,

131
00:06:33.060 --> 00:06:36.100
the most upright of them a thorn hedge.

132
00:06:36.100 --> 00:06:40.060
The day of your punishment has come now.

133
00:06:40.060 --> 00:06:42.380
Their confusion is at hand.

134
00:06:42.380 --> 00:06:44.900
Goes on to talk more about how

135
00:06:46.100 --> 00:06:48.700
it's hard to put trust in anyone else.

136
00:06:48.700 --> 00:06:50.820
It's hard to even trust family members.

137
00:06:51.460 --> 00:06:54.460
I think this sentiment is one that we can all

138
00:06:55.460 --> 00:06:57.780
relate to somewhat, whether it might be a person

139
00:06:57.780 --> 00:06:59.660
or it might even be in yourself,

140
00:06:59.660 --> 00:07:01.580
where you have a hard time trusting the things

141
00:07:01.580 --> 00:07:03.860
that you even feel or the things that you're thinking

142
00:07:03.860 --> 00:07:05.740
or the things that are coming out of someone's mouth

143
00:07:05.740 --> 00:07:09.740
and it's so difficult to know what is real.

144
00:07:11.260 --> 00:07:15.260
And so as we kind of look at this passage Psalm 12

145
00:07:15.260 --> 00:07:16.420
in these two different groups,

146
00:07:16.420 --> 00:07:19.420
the wicked and the wicked.

147
00:07:19.460 --> 00:07:23.100
It's the wicked that are described here in the faithful.

148
00:07:24.180 --> 00:07:28.660
I wanted to just keep our mind on what is David's heart cry

149
00:07:28.660 --> 00:07:29.500
for God to help?

150
00:07:29.500 --> 00:07:31.060
Why is he asking for help?

151
00:07:31.060 --> 00:07:32.660
What does he need for help?

152
00:07:33.820 --> 00:07:35.620
And what can we learn about the faithful?

153
00:07:35.620 --> 00:07:36.740
What can we learn about the wicked?

154
00:07:36.740 --> 00:07:39.460
And what can we learn about the Lord ultimately?

155
00:07:42.260 --> 00:07:44.660
So let's take the wicked first.

156
00:07:44.660 --> 00:07:47.660
What can we learn about the wicked from this chapter?

157
00:07:48.660 --> 00:07:52.420
Well, to start off, they do not seek after God.

158
00:07:53.820 --> 00:07:56.820
David here is seeking after God's help,

159
00:07:56.820 --> 00:07:59.340
crying out, save, oh Lord, the wicked

160
00:07:59.340 --> 00:08:02.500
are not seen asking for God to save them.

161
00:08:02.500 --> 00:08:05.540
Instead in verse four, it says,

162
00:08:05.540 --> 00:08:07.180
with our tongue we will prevail,

163
00:08:07.180 --> 00:08:10.900
our lips are with us, who is master over us.

164
00:08:12.220 --> 00:08:14.900
They see themselves as their own master.

165
00:08:18.660 --> 00:08:21.140
In other words, they think they're smart enough

166
00:08:21.140 --> 00:08:23.220
to use their words to get what they want.

167
00:08:24.340 --> 00:08:28.660
So second, how is it that they use their words?

168
00:08:30.740 --> 00:08:33.580
Well, in verse two, it says,

169
00:08:33.580 --> 00:08:35.580
they utter lies to their neighbor

170
00:08:36.580 --> 00:08:39.100
with flattering lips in a devil heart they speak.

171
00:08:40.940 --> 00:08:45.220
So they seek to use their words to manipulate others

172
00:08:45.500 --> 00:08:49.060
in order to get whatever it is they want.

173
00:08:50.660 --> 00:08:55.260
They're hypocrites, they say whatever is convenient to them,

174
00:08:55.260 --> 00:08:56.620
it's hard to trust them.

175
00:08:57.700 --> 00:09:01.460
Being around someone like this is like walking on eggshells.

176
00:09:01.460 --> 00:09:04.380
And I can honestly think of many times in my life

177
00:09:04.380 --> 00:09:08.820
where flattery seems like the better course of action

178
00:09:08.820 --> 00:09:10.140
than honesty.

179
00:09:12.300 --> 00:09:14.380
And so if you look at this and you look at like,

180
00:09:14.420 --> 00:09:17.140
okay, well, what does it mean to have flattering lips?

181
00:09:18.220 --> 00:09:21.420
There's really two sins, I guess you could say,

182
00:09:21.420 --> 00:09:24.820
that are underneath that term.

183
00:09:24.820 --> 00:09:28.060
One is this flattery that is external.

184
00:09:28.060 --> 00:09:32.020
So it might be this building someone else up

185
00:09:32.020 --> 00:09:33.860
and praising someone else, not for the sake

186
00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:35.940
of just building them up, but ultimately,

187
00:09:35.940 --> 00:09:38.860
it's kind of like trying to get whatever it is they want.

188
00:09:38.860 --> 00:09:41.500
So I'm gonna build you up so that I get what I want

189
00:09:41.500 --> 00:09:43.940
in this secretive kind of way.

190
00:09:44.140 --> 00:09:48.740
This using our words to manipulate other people

191
00:09:49.820 --> 00:09:52.500
in ways that they might not even notice.

192
00:09:52.500 --> 00:09:53.980
You might say to yourself, after all,

193
00:09:53.980 --> 00:09:55.660
it's just like a little white lie.

194
00:09:56.740 --> 00:09:58.260
What harm could it cause?

195
00:09:59.480 --> 00:10:00.740
Who is it going to hurt?

196
00:10:02.060 --> 00:10:05.220
And sometimes it might seem like the better course

197
00:10:05.220 --> 00:10:06.500
of action than honesty,

198
00:10:08.900 --> 00:10:12.260
while secretly the true motivation is maybe just

199
00:10:12.300 --> 00:10:14.020
to make people think better.

200
00:10:16.660 --> 00:10:18.460
David feels that he cannot trust the words

201
00:10:18.460 --> 00:10:20.980
of anyone around him in this moment.

202
00:10:20.980 --> 00:10:22.940
There's no one else that he can trust.

203
00:10:25.620 --> 00:10:27.780
The second kind of sin, I think that's called out here

204
00:10:27.780 --> 00:10:29.940
in the Wicked is the sin of pride.

205
00:10:31.220 --> 00:10:34.600
It's the using your words to build yourself up

206
00:10:34.600 --> 00:10:36.900
even at the expense of everyone else.

207
00:10:37.780 --> 00:10:40.020
And so another thing that we see in the Wicked

208
00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:43.980
is that in verse three says,

209
00:10:43.980 --> 00:10:46.140
may the Lord cut off all flattering lips,

210
00:10:46.140 --> 00:10:48.340
the tongue that makes great boasts.

211
00:10:49.740 --> 00:10:54.660
They use their words here to boast about themselves,

212
00:10:54.660 --> 00:10:57.620
ultimately at the cost of others,

213
00:10:57.620 --> 00:11:00.620
or more specifically, when we get to verse five,

214
00:11:00.620 --> 00:11:03.780
at the expense of the poor and needy.

215
00:11:07.580 --> 00:11:08.420
I'm gonna pause here.

216
00:11:08.460 --> 00:11:11.100
This is a tough word too,

217
00:11:11.100 --> 00:11:13.340
because as I think about my own life

218
00:11:13.340 --> 00:11:15.900
and times when I've used my words,

219
00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:20.340
I often am thinking only about what I gain or myself.

220
00:11:21.660 --> 00:11:23.900
So it's humbling to come to this text

221
00:11:23.900 --> 00:11:25.580
and hear this description of the Wicked

222
00:11:25.580 --> 00:11:29.480
as this prideful arrogant or flattering other people.

223
00:11:33.740 --> 00:11:34.740
C.S. Lewis in his book,

224
00:11:34.780 --> 00:11:35.580
The One Near Christianity,

225
00:11:35.580 --> 00:11:38.500
referred to pride as the great sin.

226
00:11:38.500 --> 00:11:41.120
He called it out as the utmost of evil.

227
00:11:41.120 --> 00:11:43.780
And one of his main reasons for doing that

228
00:11:43.780 --> 00:11:45.280
can be summarized here.

229
00:11:46.340 --> 00:11:51.340
He says, pride gets no pleasure out of having something

230
00:11:51.580 --> 00:11:54.700
only out of having more of it than the next man.

231
00:11:55.660 --> 00:11:58.340
We say that people are proud of being rich

232
00:11:58.340 --> 00:12:02.500
or clever or good looking, but they are not.

233
00:12:02.500 --> 00:12:05.020
They are proud of being richer or clever

234
00:12:05.020 --> 00:12:07.580
or better looking than others.

235
00:12:07.580 --> 00:12:10.980
If someone else became equally rich or clever

236
00:12:10.980 --> 00:12:14.140
or good looking, there would be nothing to be proud about.

237
00:12:15.500 --> 00:12:18.420
It is the comparison that makes you proud,

238
00:12:18.420 --> 00:12:20.860
the pleasure of being above the rest.

239
00:12:22.460 --> 00:12:25.540
So the proud are boastful because they see themselves

240
00:12:25.540 --> 00:12:27.040
as better than others.

241
00:12:28.060 --> 00:12:32.180
And they ultimately boast in order to call attention to it.

242
00:12:32.180 --> 00:12:35.620
And because pride is by its very nature competitive,

243
00:12:35.620 --> 00:12:38.260
it becomes necessary to boast in oneself

244
00:12:38.260 --> 00:12:41.860
at the expense of those in worse condition around them.

245
00:12:44.820 --> 00:12:46.300
So what is the third thing?

246
00:12:46.300 --> 00:12:49.740
How do they, what is it that they use their words to do?

247
00:12:49.740 --> 00:12:52.940
So we know that they are using their words for pride

248
00:12:52.940 --> 00:12:54.940
to build themselves up.

249
00:12:55.900 --> 00:13:00.540
Well, in verse five, we see that they use their words.

250
00:13:00.580 --> 00:13:03.980
Ultimately, it says, because the poor are plundered

251
00:13:03.980 --> 00:13:04.940
and because the needy grown.

252
00:13:04.940 --> 00:13:06.980
And I think this comes immediately after talking

253
00:13:06.980 --> 00:13:10.100
about how the wicked use their words.

254
00:13:10.100 --> 00:13:12.940
It's gotta be connected, that the wicked are using

255
00:13:12.940 --> 00:13:15.380
their words ultimately for the sake of boasting

256
00:13:15.380 --> 00:13:18.180
or building themselves up even at the expense of others.

257
00:13:19.700 --> 00:13:22.980
So we see this description of what the wicked person is like.

258
00:13:24.820 --> 00:13:27.820
What does this chapter say about the opposite

259
00:13:27.820 --> 00:13:28.780
or the faithful?

260
00:13:31.540 --> 00:13:35.260
Well, it's interesting.

261
00:13:36.700 --> 00:13:40.540
The faithful, they first of all, I think we can see the faithful

262
00:13:40.540 --> 00:13:45.540
